# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dapper-orm-dotnet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/data-mapper-pattern] In software engineering, the **data mapper pattern** is an architectural pattern.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/data-mapper-pattern] It was named by Martin Fowler in his 2003 book *Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture*.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/data-mapper-pattern] The interface of an object conforming to this pattern would include functions such as Create, Read, Update, and Delete, that operate on objects that represent domain entity types in a data store.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/data-mapper-pattern] A Data Mapper is a Data Access Layer that performs bidirectional transfer of data between a persistent data store (often a relational database) and an in-memory data representation (the domain layer).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/data-mapper-pattern] The goal of the pattern is to keep the in-memory representation and the persistent data store independent of each other and the data mapper itself.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/data-mapper-pattern] This is useful when one needs to model and enforce strict business processes on the data in the domain layer that do not map neatly to the persistent data store.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/data-mapper-pattern] The layer is composed of one or more mappers (or Data Access Objects), performing the data transfer.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/data-mapper-pattern] Generic mappers will handle many different domain entity types; dedicated mappers will handle one or a few.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/data-mapper-pattern] Implementations of the concept can be found in various frameworks for many programming environments.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] The **.NET** platform (pronounced as "*dot net"*; formerly named **.NET Core**) is a free and open-source, managed computer software framework for Windows, Linux, and macOS operating systems.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] It is a cross-platform successor to the .NET Framework.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] The project is mainly developed by Microsoft employees by way of the .NET Foundation and is today released under an MIT License.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] New versions of the .NET platform are released annually, typically in November.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] The most recent version of .NET is .NET 10, released in November 2025, which is a long-term support (LTS) version, and is scheduled to receive updates until November 2028.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] In the late 1990s, Microsoft began developing a managed code runtime and programming language (C#) which it billed together as part of the ".NET platform", with the core runtime and software libraries comprising the .NET Framework.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Soon after the announcement of the C# language at the Professional Developers Conference in 2000 and previews of its software became available, Microsoft began a standardization effort through ECMA for what it dubbed the Common Language Infrastructure.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] The company continued development and support of its own implementation as proprietary, closed source software in the meantime.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Miguel de Icaza describes .NET Core as a "redesigned version of .NET that is based on the simplified version of the class libraries", and Microsoft's Immo Landwerth explained that .NET Core would be "the foundation of all future .NET platforms".
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] At the time of the announcement, the initial release of the .NET Core project had been seeded with a subset of the libraries' source code and coincided with the relicensing of Microsoft's existing .NET reference source away from the restrictions of the Ms-RSL.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Landwerth acknowledged the disadvantages of the formerly selected shared license, explaining that it made codename Rotor "a non-starter" as a community-developed open source project because it did not meet the criteria of an Open Source Initiative (OSI) approved license.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] .NET Core 1.0 was released on June 27, 2016, along with Microsoft Visual Studio 2015 Update 3, which enables .NET Core development. .NET Core 1.0.4 and .NET Core 1.1.1 were released along with .NET Core Tools 1.0 and Visual Studio 2017 on March 7, 2017.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] .NET Core 2.0 was released on August 14, 2017, along with Visual Studio 2017 15.3, ASP.NET Core 2.0, and Entity Framework Core 2.0. .NET Core 2.1 was released on May 30, 2018.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] NET Core 2.2 was released on December 4, 2018.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] .NET Core 3 was released on September 23, 2019.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] NET Core 3 adds support for Windows desktop application development and significant performance improvements throughout the base library.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] In November 2020, Microsoft released .NET 5.0.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] The "Core" branding was abandoned and version 4.0 was skipped to avoid conflation with .NET Framework, of which the latest releases had all used 4.x versioning for all significant (non-bugfix) releases since 2010.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] .NET Core Runtime roughly uses semantic versioning, the *major.minor.patch* format.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Major versions are incremented with "significant changes", API-breaking changes, or with the major version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Minor versions are incremented with the addition of API features, dependencies, or with the minor version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Patch versions are given for bug fixes, new platform support, or other changes not included above.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] As of 2019, runtime versions are backwards-compatible within the same major version number.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] For example, .NET Core 2.2 is able to run programs built for .NET Core 2.1.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Runtime versions in the same minor version.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] This appears to have relaxed since .NET 5.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] A "roll-forward" behavior allows any .NET program to be run on any newer version given the correct settings.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] The SDK does not use semantic versioning.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] As of 2019, it supports targeting *every* runtime version prior to its maximum supported version.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] As of 2020, this extends down to .NET Framework runtimes as well, though downloading an additional "targeting pack" from NuGet may be necessary.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] The major and minor versions of an SDK always matches the major and minor versions of the runtime it contains or is aligned for.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Alpine Linux, which primarily supports and uses musl libc, is supported since .NET Core 2.1.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Windows Arm64 is natively supported since .NET 5.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Previously, .NET on ARM meant applications compiled for the x86 architecture and run through the ARM emulation layer.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Linux .NET runs on Power ISA to some extent since .NET 7, officially no support is claimed by Microsoft but .NET does contain code for Power ISA compatibility for Linux systems and is able to be compiled for Power ISA systems specifically 64 bit Little Endian variant.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] .NET fully supports C# and F# (and C++/CLI as of 3.1; only enabled on Windows) and supports Visual Basic .NET (for version 15.5 in .NET Core 5.0.100-preview.4, and some old versions supported in old .NET Core).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] VB.NET compiles and runs on .NET, but as of .NET Core 3.1, the separate Visual Basic Runtime is not implemented.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Microsoft initially announced that .NET Core 3 would include the Visual Basic Runtime, but after two years the timeline for such support was updated to .NET 5.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] .NET supports the following cross-platform scenarios: ASP.NET Core web apps, command-line/console apps, libraries and Universal Windows Platform apps.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Prior to .NET Core 3.0, it did not implement Windows Forms or Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), which render the standard GUI for desktop software on Windows.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] However, from .NET Core 3 on, it started implementing them along with Universal Windows Platform (UWP).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] It was also possible to write cross-platform graphical applications using .NET with the GTK# language-binding for the GTK widget toolkit, but this binding has not been maintained for many years.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Unlike .NET Framework, which is serviced using Windows Update, .NET used to rely on its package manager to receive updates.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Since December 2020, however, .NET updates started being delivered via Windows Update as well.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] NuGet serves as the primary distribution mechanism for libraries and tools in the .NET ecosystem, including third-party components that extend core functionality.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] Among these are ADO.NET-compatible data providers, which offer database connectivity for systems beyond the default SQL Server support.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] These providers enable direct access to databases such as Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and others, and are commonly used in applications that require cross-platform data access, integration with ORM technologies, or support for specific database features.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] The two main components of .NET are CoreCLR and CoreFX, which are comparable to the Common Language Runtime (CLR) and the Framework Class Library (FCL) of the .NET Framework's Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) implementation.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] As an implementation of CLI's Standard Libraries, CoreFX shares a subset of .NET Framework APIs, however, it also comes with its own APIs that are not part of the .NET Framework.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] A variant of the .NET library is used for UWP.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] The .NET command-line interface offers an execution entry point for operating systems and provides developer services like compilation and package management.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] The official community mascot of .NET is the .NET Bot (stylized as "dotnet bot" or "dotnet-bot").
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] The dotnet bot served as the placeholder developer for the initial check-in of the .NET source code when it was open-sourced.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/net] It has since been used as the official mascot.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] In database management systems (DBMS), a **prepared statement**, **parameterized statement**, (not to be confused with **parameterized query**) is a feature where the database pre-compiles SQL code and stores the results, separating it from data.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] A prepared statement takes the form of a pre-compiled template into which constant values are substituted during each execution, and typically use SQL DML statements such as INSERT, SELECT, or UPDATE.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] **Compile**: The DBMS compiles (parses, optimizes and translates) the statement template, and stores the result without executing it.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] **Execute**: The application supplies (or *binds*) values for the parameters of the statement template, and the DBMS executes the statement (possibly returning a result).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] The application may request the DBMS to execute the statement many times with different values.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] In the above example, the application might supply the values "bike" for the first parameter and "10900" for the second parameter, and then later the values "shoes" and "7400".
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] The alternative to a prepared statement is calling SQL directly from the application source code in a way that combines code and data.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] Not all optimization can be performed at the time the statement template is compiled, for two reasons: the best plan may depend on the specific values of the parameters, and the best plan may change as tables and indexes change over time.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] On the other hand, if a query is executed only once, server-side prepared statements can be slower because of the additional round-trip to the server.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] Implementation limitations may also lead to performance penalties; for example, some versions of MySQL did not cache results of prepared queries.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] A stored procedure, which is also precompiled and stored on the server for later execution, has similar advantages.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] Unlike a stored procedure, a prepared statement is not normally written in a procedural language and cannot use or modify variables or use control flow structures, relying instead on the declarative database query language.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] Due to their simplicity and client-side emulation, prepared statements are more portable across vendors.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] Major DBMSs, including SQLite, MySQL, Oracle, IBM Db2, Microsoft SQL Server and PostgreSQL support prepared statements.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] Prepared statements are normally executed through a non-SQL binary protocol for efficiency and protection from SQL injection, but with some DBMSs such as MySQL prepared statements are also available using a SQL syntax for debugging purposes.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] A number of programming languages support prepared statements in their standard libraries and will emulate them on the client side even if the underlying DBMS does not support them, including Java's JDBC, Perl's DBI, PHP's PDO and Python's DB-API.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] Client-side emulation can be faster for queries which are executed only once, by reducing the number of round trips to the server, but is usually slower for queries executed many times.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] It resists SQL injection attacks equally effectively.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] Many types of SQL injection attacks can be eliminated by *disabling literals*, effectively requiring the use of prepared statements; as of 2007 only H2 supports this feature.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] In C++ MySQL Connector/C++ X DevAPI, preparation is done implicitly using the library's API.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] ADO.NET `SqlCommand` will accept any type for the `value` parameter of `AddWithValue`, and type conversion occurs automatically.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] Note the use of "named parameters" (i.e.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] `"@username"`) rather than `"?"`—this allows you to use a parameter multiple times and in any arbitrary order within the query command text.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] However, the AddWithValue method should not be used with variable length data types, like varchar and nvarchar.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] This is because .NET assumes the length of the parameter to be the length of the given value, rather than getting the actual length from the database via reflection.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] The consequence of this is that a different query plan is compiled and stored for each different length.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] In general, the maximum number of "duplicate" plans is the product of the lengths of the variable length columns as specified in the database.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] `command.Parameters.Add(ParamName, VarChar, ParamLength).Value = ParamValue`, where ParamLength is the length as specified in the database.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] Since the standard Add method needs to be used for variable length data types, it is a good habit to use it for all parameter types.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] The placeholder parameter syntax differs depending on your database.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] MySQL, SQL Server and SQLite use the ? notation, but PostgreSQL uses the $N notation.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/prepared-statement] Java `PreparedStatement` provides "setters" (`setInt(int), setString(String), setDouble(double),` etc.) for all major built-in data types.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/relational-database] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:dapper-orm-dotnet/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
